This paper is about social influence and its measurement, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of social computing. The most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which specifically deals with the study of social networks and their impact on information dissemination, behavior, and influence. The second likely sub-category is cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences), which covers research on social phenomena and human behavior. The third likely sub-category is cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy), which includes research on the security and privacy implications of social networks and online behavior. The fourth likely sub-category is cs.MA (Multiagent Systems), which deals with the study of agents and their interactions in social networks. The fifth likely sub-category is cs.IR (Information Retrieval), which includes research on the analysis and retrieval of information from social networks.
